{{Infobox Museum |name = Castell Henllys Iron Age Fort |image = Castell Henllys - geograph.org.uk - 67364.jpg |imagesize = 240px |caption = |map_type = Wales |map_caption = Location within Wales |coordinates = {{coord|52.017|-4.745|display=inline,title}} |established = |dissolved = |location = |type = [[Archaeological open-air museum]] |visitors = |director = |curator = |publictransit = |website = [https://www.castellhenllys.com/ Castell Henllys] }}
'''Castell Henllys''' ([[Welsh language|Welsh]], "castle of the old court") is an important [[archaeology|archaeological]] site in north [[Pembrokeshire]], [[Wales]], between [[Newport, Pembrokeshire|Newport]] and [[Cardigan, Ceredigion|Cardigan]].
This [[Iron Age]] [[hillfort]] has been the subject of an ongoing excavation for more than twenty years, accompanied by an exercise in [[reconstruction archaeology]] whereby experiments in prehistoric farming have been practised. Four [[Roundhouse_(dwelling)|roundhouse]]s and a [[granary]] have been reconstructed on their original Iron Age foundations, some 2,000 years old, the only site in Britain where this has been done.<ref>{{cite news|work=Tivyside Advertiser|date=5 July 2018|author=Dave Parkinson|title=Roundhouse built on site of existing Iron Age fort near Cardigan|url=http://www.tivysideadvertiser.co.uk/news/16334564.roundhouse-built-on-site-of-existing-iron-age-fort-near-cardigan/|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>
During the summer the site acts as a training excavation for young archaeologists. The site is a popular visitor attraction<ref>{{cite web|title=Visit Pembrokeshire: Castell Henllys Iron Age Fort|url=http://www.visitpembrokeshire.com/attractions-events/castell-henllys-iron-age-fort/|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> and is owned by the [[Pembrokeshire Coast National Park]].
